<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-formats" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Output Formats</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The <c>bookdown</c> package primarily supports three types of output
      formats: HTML, LaTeX/PDF, and e-books. In this chapter, we introduce the
      possible options for these formats. Output formats can be specified
      either in the YAML metadata of the first Rmd file of the book, or in a
      separate YAML file named <c>_output.yml</c> under the root directory of
      the book.
    </p>

    <p>Here is a brief example of YAML metadata in a book source file:</p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
title: "An Impressive Book"
author: "Li Lei and Han Meimei"
output:
  bookdown::gitbook:
    lib_dir: assets
    split_by: section
    config:
      toolbar:
        position: static
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    keep_tex: true
  bookdown::html_book:
    css: toc.css
documentclass: book
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>Here is an example of <c>_output.yml</c>:</p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>bookdown::gitbook:
  lib_dir: assets
  split_by: section
  config:
    toolbar:
      position: static
bookdown::pdf_book:
  keep_tex: true
bookdown::html_book:
  css: toc.css</input>
    </program>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="html">
    <title>HTML</title>

    <p>
      The main difference between rendering a book with <c>bookdown</c> and
      rendering a single R Markdown document to HTML is that a book will
      generate multiple HTML pages by default—normally one HTML file per
      chapter. This makes it easier to bookmark certain chapters, share URLs,
      and load the book more quickly in the browser.
    </p>

    <p>The chapter introduces four HTML styles:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>the GitBook style</p></li>
      <li><p>the three-column Bootstrap style</p></li>
      <li><p>the default Bootstrap style</p></li>
      <li><p>the Tufte style</p></li>
    </ul>

    <subsection xml:id="gitbook-style">
      <title>GitBook style</title>

      <p>
        The GitBook style was borrowed from GitBook and provides a layout with
        a sidebar showing the table of contents on the left and the main body
        of the book on the right. The design is responsive to the window size,
        so navigation buttons and the sidebar adapt on narrower screens.
      </p>

      <p>
        The easiest way to get started writing a new <c>gitbook</c> is to use
        the RStudio Project Wizard, or create the same template with
        <c>bookdown::create_gitbook()</c> from the R console.
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>bookdown::gitbook(
  fig_caption = TRUE, number_sections = TRUE, self_contained = FALSE,
  anchor_sections = TRUE, lib_dir = "libs",
  global_numbering = !number_sections, pandoc_args = NULL,
  extra_dependencies = list(), ..., template = "default",
  split_by = c("chapter", "section", "0", "1", "2", "3", "4", "5",
               "6", "chapter+number", "section+number", "0+number",
               "1+number", "2+number", "3+number", "4+number",
               "5+number", "6+number", "rmd", "none"),
  split_bib = TRUE, config = list(), table_css = TRUE,
  code_folding = c("none", "show", "hide")
)</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        Most arguments are passed to <c>rmarkdown::html_document()</c>,
        including <c>fig_caption</c>, <c>lib_dir</c>, and <c>...</c>. The
        chapter strongly recommends using <c>fig_caption = TRUE</c> so figures
        are properly captioned and can float correctly in LaTeX output.
      </p>

      <p>
        Beyond the inherited HTML-document options, <c>gitbook()</c> adds
        <c>split_by</c>, <c>split_bib</c>, and <c>config</c>. The
        <c>split_by</c> argument controls how the HTML output is split into
        pages.
      </p>

      <program language="markdown">
        <input># An Introduction {#introduction}

The default identifier is `an-introduction` but we changed
it to `introduction`.</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        The <c>config</c> option contains many user-interface settings,
        including the TOC, toolbar, search, font settings, sharing buttons, and
        information button. The Rmd chapter shows these defaults as YAML.
      </p>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>bookdown::gitbook:
  config:
    toc:
      collapse: subsection
      scroll_highlight: true
      before: null
      after: null
    toolbar:
      position: fixed
    edit : null
    download: null
    search:
      engine: lunr
      options: null
    fontsettings:
      theme: white
      family: sans
      size: 2
    sharing:
      facebook: true
      github: false
      twitter: true
      linkedin: false
      weibo: false
      instapaper: false
      vk: false
      whatsapp: false
      all: ['facebook', 'twitter', 'linkedin', 'weibo', 'instapaper']
    info: true</input>
      </program>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>toc:
  before: |
    <li><a href="...">My Awesome Book</a></li>
    <li><a href="...">John Smith</a></li>
  after: |
    <li><a href="https://github.com/rstudio/bookdown">
    Proudly published with bookdown</a></li></input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>```{r gitbook-toolbar, echo=FALSE, fig.cap='The GitBook toolbar.', out.width='100%'}
knitr::include_graphics('images/gitbook.png', dpi = NA)
```</input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-gitbook-toolbar-pretext">
        <title>The GitBook toolbar.</title>
        <image source="../assets/images/gitbook.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of the GitBook toolbar used in the output formats chapter.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The toolbar lets readers toggle the sidebar, search the book, change
        font and theme settings, use edit/history/view links, download other
        formats, share links on social networks, and open the keyboard-shortcut
        information panel.
      </p>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>fontsettings:
  theme: night
  family: serif
  size: 3</input>
      </program>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>download: ["book.pdf", "book.epub"]
download: ["pdf", "epub", "mobi"]</input>
      </program>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>download:
  - ["book.pdf", "PDF"]
  - ["book.epub", "EPUB"]</input>
      </program>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>---
title: "An Awesome Book"
author: "John Smith"
description: "This book introduces the ABC theory, and ..."
url: 'https\://bookdown.org/john/awesome/'
github-repo: "john/awesome"
cover-image: "images/cover.png"
apple-touch-icon: "touch-icon.png"
apple-touch-icon-size: 120
favicon: "favicon.ico"
---</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="bs4-book">
      <title>Three-column Bootstrap style</title>

      <p>
        The <c>bs4_book()</c> output format is built with Bootstrap and is
        designed to provide a clean reading experience on phones, tablets, and
        desktop screens. On wide screens, the layout includes three columns for
        chapters, chapter content, and within-chapter navigation.
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>```{r fig.align='center', echo=FALSE, fig.link='https://mastering-shiny.org', fig.cap="Home page of a book with the three-column Bootstrap style.", out.width=if(knitr::is_latex_output()) '100%'}
knitr::include_graphics('images/bs4-book.png', dpi = NA)
```</input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-bs4-book-pretext">
        <title>Home page of a book with the three-column Bootstrap style.</title>
        <image source="../assets/images/bs4-book.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of a book home page rendered with the bs4_book style.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>The chapter highlights these main features of <c>bs4_book</c>:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><p>customizable colors and fonts with the <c>bslib</c> package</p></li>
        <li><p>built-in search broken down by section</p></li>
        <li><p>a within-chapter sidebar table of contents</p></li>
        <li><p>typography tuned for different device sizes</p></li>
        <li><p>inline footnotes</p></li>
        <li><p>syntax highlighting and autolinking via <c>downlit</c></p></li>
        <li><p>enhanced metadata for social sharing</p></li>
        <li><p>repository links for source viewing or suggesting edits</p></li>
      </ul>

      <program language="r">
        <input>bookdown::bs4_book(
  theme = bs4_book_theme(), repo = NULL, ..., lib_dir = "libs",
  pandoc_args = NULL, extra_dependencies = NULL, template = "default",
  split_bib = FALSE, footnotes_inline = TRUE
)</input>
      </program>

      <subsubsection xml:id="writing-a-bs4-book">
        <title>Writing a bs4_book</title>

        <p>
          The easiest way to start a <c>bs4_book</c> is the RStudio Project
          Wizard, or <c>bookdown::create_bs4_book()</c> from the R console.
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>```{r new-bs4-book, fig.align='center', echo=FALSE, fig.cap="Screenshot of the RStudio Project Wizard for creating a new bookdown project."}
knitr::include_graphics('images/new-bs4-book.png', dpi = NA)
```</input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="fig-new-bs4-book-pretext">
          <title>Screenshot of the RStudio Project Wizard for creating a new bookdown project.</title>
          <image source="../assets/images/new-bs4-book.png" width="90%">
            <description>
              <p>The RStudio Project Wizard with the bs4_book option selected.</p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          This style is designed for books that use one chapter per page, which
          means each <c>.Rmd</c> file should contain a single chapter and start
          with one first-level heading.
        </p>

        <program language="markdown">
          <input>#   A chapter

##  A section

### A subsection</input>
        </program>

        <p>The chapter also gives this example <c>index.Rmd</c> YAML header:</p>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>---
title: "A Minimal Book Example"
author: "Jane Doe"
date: "`r Sys.Date()`"
site: bookdown::bookdown_site
output: bookdown::bs4_book
url: https://bookdown.org/janedoe/bookdown-demo
cover-image: cover.png
description: |
  This is a minimal example of using the bookdown package to write a book.
  The output format for this example is bookdown::bs4_book.
---</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="styling-customization">
        <title>Styling &amp; customization</title>

        <p>
          The <c>bs4_book()</c> format builds on Bootstrap and uses the
          <c>bslib</c> package for easy customization of colors and fonts.
        </p>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  theme:
    primary: "#0d6efd"</input>
        </program>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  theme:
    primary: "#0d6efd"
    base_font:
      google: Sen
    heading_font:
      google:
        family: Bitter
        wght: 200
    code_font:
      google:
        family: DM Mono
        local: false</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="callout-blocks">
        <title>Callout blocks</title>

        <p>
          Callout blocks can make important parts of the narrative stand out.
          The <c>bs4_book</c> style includes predefined callout blocks such as
          <c>.rmdnote</c>, <c>.rmdcaution</c>, <c>.rmdimportant</c>,
          <c>.rmdtip</c>, and <c>.rmdwarning</c>.
        </p>

        <program language="markdown">
          <input>::: {.rmdnote}
The `bs4_book` style also includes an `.rmdnote` callout block
like this one.

```{r collapse=TRUE}`r ''``
head(beaver1, n = 5)
```
:::</input>
        </program>

        <program language="r">
          <input>```{r bs4-note, fig.align='center', echo=FALSE, fig.cap="A special callout block."}
knitr::include_graphics('images/rmd-note.png', dpi = NA)
```</input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="fig-bs4-note-pretext">
          <title>A special callout block.</title>
          <image source="../assets/images/rmd-note.png" width="85%">
            <description>
              <p>An example of a styled callout block in the bs4_book theme.</p>
            </description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  theme:
    primary: "#0d6efd"
    danger:  "#dc3545"
    success: "#198754"
    info:    "#0dcaf0"
    warning: "#ffc107"</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="html-metadata">
        <title>HTML metadata</title>

        <p>
          <c>bs4_book()</c> uses Pandoc variables from <c>index.Rmd</c> to
          generate HTML <c>meta</c> tags, and it also creates unique chapter
          descriptions automatically from chapter content.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="bs4-book-footnotes">
        <title>Inline Footnotes</title>

        <p>
          The <c>bs4_book</c> format makes footnotes show inline on hover. You
          can opt out and keep footnotes at the bottom by setting
          <c>footnotes_inline = FALSE</c>.
        </p>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  footnotes_inline: false</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="references-bibliography">
        <title>References/Bibliography</title>

        <p>
          If you use a footnote citation style, readers can view references near
          the text where they are cited. The chapter recommends downloading a
          footnote-style CSL file, for example from Zotero.
        </p>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bibliography: refs.bib
csl: chicago-fullnote-bibliography.csl</input>
        </program>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>suppress-bibliography: true</input>
        </program>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  split_bib: true</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="specifying-the-repository">
        <title>Specifying the repository</title>

        <p>
          You can specify a source repository so readers can view chapter source
          files or suggest edits.
        </p>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  repo:
    base: https://github.com/hadley/ggplot2-book
    branch: main</input>
        </program>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  repo:
    base: https://github.com/hadley/ggplot2-book
    branch: main
    subdir: book</input>
        </program>

        <program language="yaml">
          <input>bookdown::bs4_book:
  repo:
    base: https://github.com/hadley/ggplot2-book
    branch: main
    subdir: book
    icon: "fas fa-air-freshener"</input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="bootstrap-style">
      <title>The default Bootstrap style</title>

      <p>
        The default Bootstrap style in <c>bookdown</c> uses
        <c>html_book()</c>, which in turn is a special case of
        <c>html_chapters()</c>. Most options from
        <c>rmarkdown::html_document()</c> still apply.
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>bookdown::html_chapters(
  toc = TRUE, number_sections = TRUE, fig_caption = TRUE, lib_dir = "libs",
  template = bookdown_file("templates/default.html"),
  global_numbering = !number_sections, pandoc_args = NULL, ...,
  base_format = rmarkdown::html_document, split_bib = TRUE,
  page_builder = build_chapter,
  split_by = c("chapter", "section", "0", "1", "2", "3", "4", "5",
               "6", "chapter+number", "section+number", "0+number",
               "1+number", "2+number", "3+number", "4+number",
               "5+number", "6+number", "rmd", "none")
)</input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>bookdown::html_book(...)</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        The chapter explains that custom HTML templates must contain three pairs
        of special HTML comments marking the title, TOC, and body sections.
      </p>

      <program language="html">
        <input>&lt;!--bookdown:title:start--&gt;
&lt;!--bookdown:title:end--&gt;
&lt;!--bookdown:toc:start--&gt;
&lt;!--bookdown:toc:end--&gt;
&lt;!--bookdown:body:start--&gt;
&lt;!--bookdown:body:end--&gt;</input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>```{r results='hide'}
bookdown:::bookdown_file('templates/default.html')
# you may use file.edit() to open this file
```</input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>```{r include=FALSE}
extract_fun = function(name, script) {
  x = readLines(script)
  def = paste(name, '= ')
  i = which(substr(x, 1, nchar(def)) == def)
  if (length(i) == 0) stop('Cannot find ', def, ' from ', script)
  i = i[1]
  j = which(x == '}')
  j = min(j[j > i])
  x[i:j]
}
```
```{r eval=FALSE, tidy=FALSE, code=extract_fun('build_chapter', '../../R/html.R')}
```</input>
      </program>

      <program language="html">
        <input>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;A Nice Book&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;div class="row"&gt;TOC&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class="row"&gt;
      CHAPTER BODY
      &lt;p&gt;
        &lt;button&gt;PREVIOUS&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;button&gt;NEXT&lt;/button&gt;
      &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</input>
      </program>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>---
output:
  bookdown::html_book:
    toc: true
    css: toc.css
---</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="tufte-style">
      <title>Tufte style</title>

      <p>
        Like the Bootstrap style, the Tufte style is provided by
        <c>tufte_html_book()</c>, a special case of <c>html_chapters()</c>
        using <c>tufte::tufte_html()</c> as the base format.
      </p>

      <p>
        It uses a main text column on the left and a margin column on the
        right, where footnotes, margin notes, references, and margin figures
        can appear.
      </p>

      <program language="yaml">
        <input>---
output:
  bookdown::tufte_html_book:
    toc: true
    css: toc.css
---</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="latex-pdf">
    <title>LaTeX/PDF</title>

    <p>
      The chapter recommends developing a book primarily in HTML and leaving
      the fine points of LaTeX typesetting until later. The LaTeX/PDF output
      format is provided by <c>pdf_book()</c>, whose main purpose is to resolve
      labels and cross-references in book output.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
documentclass: book
bibliography: [book.bib, packages.bib]
biblio-style: apalike
---</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>bookdown::pdf_book(
  toc = TRUE, number_sections = TRUE, fig_caption = TRUE, pandoc_args = NULL,
  ..., base_format = rmarkdown::pdf_document, toc_unnumbered = TRUE,
  toc_appendix = FALSE, toc_bib = FALSE, quote_footer = NULL,
  highlight_bw = FALSE
)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also notes that <c>tufte_book2()</c> is essentially
      <c>pdf_book(base_format = tufte::tufte_book)</c>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="e-books">
    <title>E-Books</title>

    <p>
      <c>bookdown</c> provides two e-book formats: EPUB and MOBI. These can be
      read on smartphones, tablets, or dedicated e-readers.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="epub">
      <title>EPUB</title>

      <p>
        To create an EPUB book, use <c>epub_book()</c>. It shares some options
        with <c>rmarkdown::html_document()</c>, and also adds EPUB-specific
        options such as <c>stylesheet</c>, <c>cover_image</c>,
        <c>metadata</c>, <c>chapter_level</c>, and <c>epub_version</c>.
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>bookdown::epub_book(
  fig_width = 5, fig_height = 4, dev = "png", fig_caption = TRUE,
  number_sections = TRUE, toc = FALSE, toc_depth = 3, stylesheet = NULL,
  cover_image = NULL, metadata = NULL, chapter_level = 1,
  epub_version = c("epub3", "epub", "epub2"), md_extensions = NULL,
  global_numbering = !number_sections, pandoc_args = NULL,
  template = "default"
)</input>
      </program>

      <p>
        The chapter explains that an EPUB book is essentially a collection of
        HTML pages bundled into one file, so many familiar bookdown features
        still work there.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="mobi">
      <title>MOBI</title>

      <p>
        MOBI e-books can be read on Kindle devices. Because Pandoc does not
        support MOBI output directly, the chapter recommends third-party tools
        such as Calibre. The <c>bookdown::calibre()</c> helper wraps the
        <c>ebook-convert</c> command-line utility.
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="a-single-document">
    <title>A single document</title>

    <p>
      Sometimes you may want automatic numbering and cross-references without
      building a full multi-file book. For that use case, <c>bookdown</c>
      provides formats such as <c>html_document2()</c>, <c>tufte_html2()</c>,
      <c>pdf_document2()</c>, <c>word_document2()</c>,
      <c>tufte_handout2()</c>, and <c>tufte_book2()</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  bookdown::html_document2: default
  bookdown::pdf_document2:
    keep_tex: true
  bookdown::word_document2:
    toc: true</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r}
bookdown::pdf_document2
```</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    base_format: rticles::jss_article</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter closes by noting that the <c>gitbook()</c> format can also
      be used for a single R Markdown document, especially when
      <c>split_by = 'none'</c> and optionally <c>self_contained = TRUE</c>.
    </p>
  </section>
</chapter>
